I don’t think you’re reading very carefully. I’m not saying we don’t impeach or that we don’t do our duty. I am saying we should consider public sentiment. Like say, yours.

So I don’t know where you are seeing me say we should ignore anything. I’m not arguing against impeachment. In fact I am arguing for taking our responsibility seriously by considering public sentiment.
Again. I challenge you to find where in my tweets tonight I say we should not impeach or hold him accountable.

No. Which is why that particular function rests in the judiciary, not the legislature. But prosecutors make charge/no charge decisions every single day.

Not exactly what I’m saying. Historically, Congress has impeached, and will again. But nothing in the constitution forces Congress to impeach in a given circumstance. If you disagree, send me the language that forces Congress to do so.

Where Matt, do I say it is “all political”? Seriously. I am a huge defender of the press. But it’s hard to do that when I take the time to engage with you and you mistate my argument. Or talk about my “look”. Are you trying to get at the truth here, or to stir the pot?
No. And I’m not arguing that.
I know the facts. And again, I’m not arguing for doing nothing. I’m arguing for acting in a smart and considered way.
I know Twitter is a universe where logic is not important, but I’m not arguing for doing nothing, I’m arguing for doing what we do in a fully informed way.
I think you’re not reading it very carefully.
As a non lawyer, I couldn’t agree more.

There is no explicit duty as there is conduct a census every 10 years. Congress decides if and when to impeach independent of the words of the constitution. That’s not controversial. It’s true. So it’s not unreasonable to try to understand where American sentiment is in deciding.

Lordy. It’s not about a look. Duty is in quotes because the constitution imposes absolutely no obligation to impeach under any circumstance. It’s at the discretion of Congress. Kinda feels like you’re looking for a lot more fireworks than you’re going to find in this quarter.

Like everything else a legislator does, there’s a mix of “knowing” and what public sentiment demands. Especially in the House, where we are called “Representative”. Impeachment could have been granted to SCOTUS, but instead, it was given to the part of our gov closest to people.

I don’t think there’s an opposition between the two in this case. Impeachment is by design a political act, not a judicial or legal one. So public sentiment is as essential (probably more) as any implicit constitutional “duty”.
Anyway, I was making an argument for care and consideration of facts and implications in however we choose to act. I expressed no view on how we should act.
I made the case, because along with the will of my constituents, that would be something I would want to know before developing intense conviction. You know, be as informed as possible before acting?

I don’t know what you heard, but I wasn’t forceful about not impeaching Trump (your words). I was forceful about making sure we had the best picture possible of how impeachment plays in Presidential swing states. Something I don’t know. See the diff?
Which is different than “tamping down” the possibility of impeachment.

No it wasn’t. Jim Himes argued that we should reflect on and consider the effect of impeachment proceedings on the chances of the President’s re-election, without prejudice. Because if he is not convicted by the Senate, 2020 is the next mechanism of accountability.
